{"lemma":"ج","slug":"ج","root":"NTWS","root_slug":"NTWS","root_link":"/words/roots/NTWS","pos":"N","pos_camel":"abbrev","paradigm":[],"frequency_in_corpus":0,"cross_references":{"qac":{"found":false},"wiktextract":{"found":true,"entry_count":3,"pos_tags":["character","noun","symbol"],"has_etymology":true,"sense_count":4},"lanes":{"found":true,"entry_ids":["n4872"],"search_url":"https://lanelexicon.com/?s=%D8%AC"}},"translations":null,"definition":{"source":"wiktextract","senses":[{"pos":"character","gloss":"The fifth letter of the Arabic alphabet, called جِيم (jīm) and written in the Arabic script; preceded by ث (ṯ) and followed by ح (ḥ).","tags":["letter"]},{"pos":"symbol","gloss":"The third numeral symbol of the Arabic alphabet (traditional abjad order, used for list numbering), written in the Arabic script; preceded by ب (b) and followed by د (d)."},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"abbreviation of جَمْع (jamʕ, “plural”)","tags":["abbreviation","alt-of"]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"abbreviation of جُزْء (juzʔ, “part”)","tags":["abbreviation","alt-of"]}]},"etymology":{"source":"wiktextract","text":"From the Nabataean letter 𐢄 (l, “gimel”), derived from the Phoenician letter 𐤂 (l, “gimel”), from an uncertain Egyptian hieroglyph (𓌙?). See also Classical Syriac ܓ (l, “gimel”), Hebrew ג (l, “gimel”), Ancient Greek Γ (G), Latin C and Latin G."},"ipa":["/d͡ʒiːm/","/d͡ʒ/","[d͡ʒ]","[ʒ]","[ɡ]","[ɟ]"],"lanes_definition":{"source":"lanes","entries":[{"entry_id":"n4872","headword_ar":"ج","root":"j","body":[{"kind":"italic_en","text":"The fifth letter of the alphabet:"},{"kind":"text","text":"called"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"jiymN","text_ar":"جِيمٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":", which is one of the names of letters of the fem. gender, but which it is allowable to make masc.: it is one of the letters termed"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"majohuwrap","text_ar":"مَجْهُورَة"},{"kind":"text","text":"[or vocal, i. e. pronounced with the voice, and not with the breath only]: and of the number of the letters termed"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"maHoquwrap","text_ar":"مَحْقُورَة"},{"kind":"text","text":", and"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"Huruwfu Alqaloqalapi","text_ar":"حُرُوفُ القَلْقَلَةِ"},{"kind":"text","text":", because it cannot be uttered in a case of pause without a strong compression, and a strong sound: and it is also one of those termed"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"$ajoriy~ap","text_ar":"شَجْرِيَّة"},{"kind":"text","text":", from"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"Al$~ajoru","text_ar":"الشَّجْرُ"},{"kind":"text","text":", which is the place of opening of the mouth. (TA.) ―         -b2-  It is sometimes substituted for"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"Y","text_ar":"ى"},{"kind":"text","text":", when the latter letter is doubled, (K,) or is so substituted by some of the Arabs; (AA, S;) as in"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"fuqayomij~N","text_ar":"فُقَيْمِجٌّ"},{"kind":"text","text":", for"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"fuqayomiY~N","text_ar":"فُقَيْمِىٌّ"},{"kind":"text","text":"; (AA, S, K;) and"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"mur~ij~N","text_ar":"مُرِّجٌّ"},{"kind":"text","text":", for"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"mur~iY~N","text_ar":"مُرِّىٌّ"},{"kind":"text","text":". (AA, S.) An Arab of the desert recited to Khalaf El-Ahmar,"},{"kind":"quote","text":"AlomuToEimaAni Al~aHoma biA@loEa$ij~i \n                        xaAliY EuwayofN waA^abuw Ealij~i"},{"kind":"text","text":"["},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"My maternal uncle is 'Oweyf, and Aboo-'Alijj, who feed with flesh-meat at nightfall"},{"kind":"text","text":"]; meaning"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"EaliY~","text_ar":"عَلِىّ"},{"kind":"text","text":"and"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"Ea$iY~","text_ar":"عَشِىّ"},{"kind":"text","text":". (S.) It is also sometimes substituted for a single"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"Y","text_ar":"ى"},{"kind":"text","text":". (S, K.) AZ gives the following ex.:"},{"kind":"quote","text":"yaA rab~i A_ino kunota qabilota Huj~atijo\n                      \n                     \n                        falaA yazaAlu $aAHijN yaA^otiyka bijo"},{"kind":"text","text":"["},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"O my Lord, if Thou accept my plea, a brayer"},{"kind":"text","text":"(or"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"mule"},{"kind":"text","text":")"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"shall not cease to bring me to Thee"},{"kind":"text","text":"(i. e. to thy temple)]; (S;) meaning"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"Huj~atiY","text_ar":"حُجَّتِى"},{"kind":"text","text":"(K) [and"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"biY","text_ar":"بِى"},{"kind":"text","text":"]."},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"A^amosajato","text_ar":"اَمْسَجَتْ"},{"kind":"text","text":"and"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"A^amosajaA","text_ar":"اَمْسَجَا"},{"kind":"text","text":"are also mentioned as occurring in a verse, for"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"A^amosato","text_ar":"اَمْسَتْ"},{"kind":"text","text":"and"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"A^amosaY","text_ar":"اَمْسَى"},{"kind":"text","text":"[because originally"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"A^amosayato","text_ar":"اَمْسَيَتْ"},{"kind":"text","text":"and"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"A^amosaYa","text_ar":"اَمْسَىَ"},{"kind":"text","text":"]. (S.) But all these substitutions are abominable, (S, Ibn-'Osfoor,) and only allowable in cases of poetical necessity. (Ibn- 'Osfoor.) It is further said that some of the Arabs, among whom were the tribe of Kudá'ah, changed"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"Y","text_ar":"ى"},{"kind":"text","text":", when occurring immediately after"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"E","text_ar":"ع"},{"kind":"text","text":", into"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"j","text_ar":"ج"},{"kind":"text","text":"; and said, for"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"raAEK","text_ar":"رَاعٍ"},{"kind":"text","text":", [originally"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"raAEiYN","text_ar":"رَاعِىٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":",]"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"raAEijN","text_ar":"رَاعِجٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":": this is what is termed"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"EajoEajapN","text_ar":"عَجْعَجَةٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":": Fr attributes the substitution of"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"j","text_ar":"ج"},{"kind":"text","text":"for"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"Y","text_ar":"ى"},{"kind":"text","text":"to the tribe of Teiyi, and some of the tribe of Asad. (TA.) ―         -b3-  Some of the Arabs also changed it into"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"Y","text_ar":"ى"},{"kind":"text","text":"; saying"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"$ayarapN","text_ar":"شَيَرَةٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":"for"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"$ajarapN","text_ar":"شَجَرَةٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":", and"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"javoyaAvN","text_ar":"جَثْيَاثٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":"for"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"javojaAvN","text_ar":"جَثْجَاثٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":", and"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"yaS~aSa","text_ar":"يَصَّصَ"},{"kind":"text","text":"for"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"jaS~aSa","text_ar":"جَصَّصَ"},{"kind":"text","text":". (AZ, S in art."},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"yS","text_ar":"يص"},{"kind":"text","text":".)       -A2-  [As a numeral,"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"j","text_ar":"ج"},{"kind":"text","text":"denotes"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"Three;"},{"kind":"text","text":"and, as such, is generally written without the dot, but thus"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"H","text_ar":"ح"},{"kind":"text","text":", or thus"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"H","text_ar":"ح"},{"kind":"text","text":", to distinguish it from"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"H","text_ar":"ح"},{"kind":"text","text":", which denotes eight.]"}],"source_refs":["K"]}]}}